    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-03-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-03-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="907"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d907">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00114A Pacific War/350: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-03-05">March 5,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received March 5—9:23 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1517. American interests—Far East. Department’s 178, January 22. Legation’s 760,
                    February 2.<note n="11" xml:id="d907fn11">Not printed; it reported that the
                        contents of Department’s telegram No. 178, January 22, had been communicated
                        to the Japanese Government on January 29 (740.00114A Pacific
                        War/318).</note> Swiss Legation, Tokyo, telegraphs: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“<hi rend="italic">Porte Parole</hi>
                            <note n="12" xml:id="d907fn12">Spokesman.</note> Japanese Foreign Office
                            informed Gorgé: (1) According views Japanese Government, strategic
                            reasons against voyage <hi rend="italic">Kanangoora</hi>
                            <note n="13" xml:id="d907fn13">See telegram No. 2061, August 29, 1942,
                                    <ref target="frus1942v01#pg_817">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1942, vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 817</ref>.</note> still stand.
                            (2) Possibility other solution will be examined appropriate services
                            although simplest solution appears send medicaments, foodstuffs,
                            correspondence, et cetera next exchange.<note n="14" xml:id="d907fn14"
                                >For correspondence on the second exchange of American and Japanese
                                nationals, see <ref target="#pg_867">pp. 867</ref> ff.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Gorgé held extended interviews Japanese Foreign Office, examined all
                            practicable means early solution. Believes exchange vessel only
                            means.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
